PINoN DEL PARAGUAY, on THE CATHARTIC NUT.

This is a shrub resembling the fig tree of our country, in its leaves, its form, and the sost- ness of its wood. The trunk and leaves, when pressed with the hand distil a milky juice abounding in serum. It bears fruit like dark walnuts, beneath the hard black rind of which lie three white kernels, covered with a white membrane and divided into as many separate compartments3 in sweetness, and in shape they resemble almonds.
